Description of the Gustaf Werner
Cyclotron and Neutron Beam Facility
Gustaf Werner Cyclotron at the
Swedberg Laboratory, Uppsala.
.The Data were Corrected For Background and For Accep-
Tance Effects.
The Recoil Protons were Detected by a Magnetic
Spectrograph, Equipped with Four Position-Sensitive
Drift Chambers and Three Trigger Scintillators. The
Proton Energy and Emission Angle was Determined by
Ray-Tracing Through the Magnetic Field. The Energy
Resolution of the Spectrometer was About 2.7 MeV FWHM.
The Errors Given are Statistical Only. In
Addition, There is a Systematic Cross Section Scale
Uncertainty of 4%
Systematic Cross Section Scale Uncertainty
Gustaf Werner Cyclotron at the
Swedberg Laboratory, Uppsala.
A Proton Beam of 98 MeV Impinged on a 110
mg/cm2 Thick Lithium Target, Enriched to 99.98 Per-
cent in 7-Li. The Unaffected Proton Beam was Bent by
A Magnet Into a Well-Shielded Beam Dump, While the
Neutrons were Collimated in a Narrow Cone at 0 Degrees
By a Heavy Collimator System, Before Entering the Ex-
Perimental Area About 8 M After the Production Target.
The Neutron Beam Spot at the Irradiation Position had
A Diameter of 7 cm. With a 3 Microamp Beam, the Neu-
Tron Yield at That Position was About 3.0E+05 Neutrons
Per Sec.
.The Neutrons Showed a Semi-Monoenergetic Neutron Spec-
Trum, with a Full Energy Peak and a Low-Energy Tail.
The Latter was Supressed by Tof and Unfolding Tech-
Niques.
.Five 180-190 mg/cm2 Target Discs of be, One 85 mg/cm2
Of Carbon, and One 50 mg/cm2 of CH2, were Mounted in
A Multitarget System with Multiwire Proportional
Chambers Between the Targets. In this Way the Energy
Loss in the Subsequent Targets Could be Corrected For,
As Well As Proper Identification of the Target Sheet.
The Ch2 Target was Used For Normalization.
